{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aae5b227-e86b-4829-b0bf-efb59d397d7a","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via constructor\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init here (runs first)\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs after constructor)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup work\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — use for synchronous setup; `TestContext` is injected via constructor parameter (MSTest 3.x+).\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement for async setup; `InitializeAsync()` runs after the constructor.\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** — implement for async teardown.\n- The older `[TestInitialize]` / `[TestCleanup]` attributes still work but the interface-based approach is preferred in MSTest 3.x.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e5557f28-6a37-438d-b6e3-70d4870ac746","outputTokens":349,"requestId":"0BE5:33AAFA:413CD6:4B9180:69F00DC3"},"id":"31ffc306-d1c4-4783-9e5f-5f1160008526","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:30:52.550Z","parentId":"7ea0dde8-4518-40dd-af83-fc5b5056d897"}
